# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: posix-standard
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:posix-standard/c-posix-library] The **C POSIX library** is a specification of a C standard library for POSIX systems.
[src:posix-standard/c-posix-library] It was developed at the same time as the ANSI C standard.
[src:posix-standard/c-posix-library] Some effort was made to make POSIX compatible with standard C; POSIX includes additional functions to those introduced in standard C.
[src:posix-standard/c-posix-library] On the other hand, the 5 headers that were added to the C standard library with C11, were not likewise included in subsequent revisions of POSIX.
[src:posix-standard/c-posix-library] It may be included in any C++ project, however the C++ standard library may have its own implementation of certain features, such as `<regex>` rather than `<regex.h>`, `<thread>` rather than `<pthread.h>`, or `<semaphore>` rather than `<semaphore.h>`.
[src:posix-standard/filesystem-hierarchy-standard] The **Filesystem Hierarchy Standard** (**FHS**) is a reference describing the conventions used for the layout of Unix-like systems.
[src:posix-standard/filesystem-hierarchy-standard] It has been made popular by its use in Linux distributions, but it is used by other Unix-like systems as well.
[src:posix-standard/filesystem-hierarchy-standard] The latest version of the standard, version 3.0, was originally released on 3 June 2015 by the Linux Foundation.
[src:posix-standard/filesystem-hierarchy-standard] It was republished on 6 November 2025 by FreeDesktop, which has since assumed maintenance of the specification.
[src:posix-standard/filesystem-hierarchy-standard] In the FHS, all files and directories appear under the root directory `/`, even if they are stored on different physical or virtual devices.
[src:posix-standard/filesystem-hierarchy-standard] Some of these directories only exist in a particular system if certain subsystems, such as the X Window System, are installed.
[src:posix-standard/filesystem-hierarchy-standard] Most of these directories exist in all Unix-like operating systems and are generally used in much the same way; however, the descriptions here are those used specifically for the FHS and are not considered authoritative for platforms other than Linux.
[src:posix-standard/filesystem-hierarchy-standard] Most Linux distributions follow the Filesystem Hierarchy Standard and declare it their own policy to maintain FHS compliance.
[src:posix-standard/filesystem-hierarchy-standard] GoboLinux and NixOS provide examples of intentionally non-compliant filesystem implementations.
[src:posix-standard/filesystem-hierarchy-standard] Some distributions generally follow the standard but deviate from it in some areas.
[src:posix-standard/filesystem-hierarchy-standard] The FHS is a "trailing standard", and so documents common practices at a point in time.
[src:posix-standard/filesystem-hierarchy-standard] Of course, times change, and distribution goals and needs call for experimentation.
[src:posix-standard/filesystem-hierarchy-standard] Modern Linux distributions include a `/run` directory as a temporary filesystem (tmpfs), which stores volatile runtime data, following the FHS version 3.0.
[src:posix-standard/filesystem-hierarchy-standard] According to the FHS version 2.3, such data were stored in `/var/run`, but this was a problem in some cases because this directory is not always available at early boot.
[src:posix-standard/filesystem-hierarchy-standard] As a result, these programs have had to resort to workarounds, such as using `/dev/.udev`, `/dev/.mdadm`, `/dev/.systemd` or `/dev/.mount` directories, even though the device directory is not intended for such data.
[src:posix-standard/filesystem-hierarchy-standard] Among other advantages, this makes the system easier to use normally with the root filesystem mounted read-only.
[src:posix-standard/filesystem-hierarchy-standard] FHS was created as the FSSTND (short for "Filesystem Standard"), largely based on similar standards for other Unix-like operating systems, such as the Version 7 Unix hier(7) from 1979, the SunOS 4.x filesystem(7) and its successor, the Solaris filesystem(7), and the FreeBSD hier(7).
[src:posix-standard/posix] The **Portable Operating System Interface** (**POSIX**; IPA: /ˈpɒz.ɪks/) is a family of standards specified by the IEEE Computer Society for maintaining compatibility between operating systems.
[src:posix-standard/posix] In order to define a level of compatibility, POSIX specifies many aspects of functionality that can be classified as application programming interface (API), command-line shell, and shell commands.
[src:posix-standard/posix] Originally derived from commonly-found Unix APIs, shells, and commands (partly because Unix was considered manufacturer-neutral), today many systems conform to the standard – including branded Unix systems, Unix-like systems, and many systems that were historically unrelated to Unix.
[src:posix-standard/posix] The standardized user command line and scripting interface were based on the UNIX System V Bourne shell.
[src:posix-standard/posix] Many user-level programs, services, and utilities (including awk, echo, ed) were also standardized, based on UNIX System V versions of them, along with required program-level services (including basic I/O: file, terminal, and network).
[src:posix-standard/posix] POSIX also defines a standard threading library API which is supported by most modern operating systems.
[src:posix-standard/posix] The POSIX standard is developed by the Austin Group (a joint working group among the IEEE, The Open Group, and the ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22/WG 15).
[src:posix-standard/posix] POSIX is intended to be used by both application and system developers.
[src:posix-standard/posix] The standards emerged from a project that began in 1984 building on work from related activity in the */usr/group* association.
[src:posix-standard/posix] Richard Stallman suggested the name *POSIX* to the IEEE instead of the former *IEEE-IX*.
[src:posix-standard/posix] The committee found it more easily pronounceable and memorable, and thus adopted it.
[src:posix-standard/posix] Originally, POSIX referred to IEEE Std 1003.1-1988, released in 1988.
[src:posix-standard/posix] The family of POSIX standards is formally designated as **IEEE 1003** and the ISO/IEC standard number is ISO/IEC 9945.
[src:posix-standard/posix] POSIX originally consisted of a single document for core services but over time additional documents were published to extend and revise the specification.
[src:posix-standard/posix] Before 1997, POSIX comprised multiple documents that were published over the course of several years.
[src:posix-standard/posix] After 1997, the Austin Group produces specifications titled Single UNIX Specification (SUS).
[src:posix-standard/posix] Over time, the group publishes versions of this specification and later POSIX is amended per some or all of a SUS version.
[src:posix-standard/posix] A SUS version consists of a collection of volumes – each for a grouping of required behavior – plus other information (outside of a volume).
[src:posix-standard/posix] Each volume is assigned an issue number that is the same for each volume of a version, but is not the same value as the version.
[src:posix-standard/posix] For example, SUS version 3 (SUSv3) includes volumes labeled issue 6.
[src:posix-standard/posix] IEEE Std 1003.1-2004 modifies POSIX.1-2001 via two minor updates or errata referred to as technical corrigenda documents.
[src:posix-standard/posix] Similar to its predecessor, POSIX.1-2008 (*IEEE Std 1003.1-2008*, 2016 Edition) consists of most of the normative material of SUSv4 (issue 7 of volumes *Base Definitions*, *System Interfaces and Headers*, *Commands and Utilities*).
[src:posix-standard/posix] SUSv4 also includes rationale information that largely applies to POSIX although not included per se.
[src:posix-standard/posix] As of POSIX 2024, the standard is aligned with the C17 language standard.
[src:posix-standard/posix] POSIX mandates 512-byte default block sizes for the df and du utilities, reflecting the typical size of blocks on disks.
[src:posix-standard/posix] When Richard Stallman and the GNU team were implementing POSIX for the GNU operating system, they objected to this on the grounds that most people think in terms of 1024 byte (or 1 KiB) blocks.
[src:posix-standard/posix] The environment variable POSIX_ME_HARDER was introduced to allow the user to force the standards-compliant behaviour.
[src:posix-standard/posix] The variable name was later changed to POSIXLY_CORRECT.
[src:posix-standard/posix] As of 2025, this variable is also used for a number of other behaviour quirks.
[src:posix-standard/posix] An operating system can be classified depending upon the degree of conformance with a POSIX standard.
[src:posix-standard/posix] Current versions of the following operating systems have been certified to conform to one or more of the various POSIX standards.
[src:posix-standard/posix] This means that they passed the automated conformance tests and their certification has not expired and the operating system has not been discontinued.
[src:posix-standard/posix] Some versions of the following operating systems had been certified to conform to one or more of the various POSIX standards.
[src:posix-standard/posix] This means that they passed the automated conformance tests.
[src:posix-standard/posix] The certification has expired and some of the operating systems have been discontinued.
[src:posix-standard/posix] The following operating systems are not certified as POSIX conformant, but they conform in large part to the standard by implementing POSIX support via a compatibility feature (usually translation libraries, or a layer atop the kernel).
[src:posix-standard/posix] Some technologies allow an operating system to enjoy a level of conformance to POSIX even though the operating system itself has little or no conformance.
[src:posix-standard/posix] Although Windows does not conform to POSIX, the following technologies provide a level of compliance.
[src:posix-standard/posix] A lightweight implementation that has POSIX-compatible header files that map POSIX APIs to call their Windows API counterparts.
[src:posix-standard/posix] An optional Windows subsystem included in Windows NT-based operating systems up to Windows 2000.
[src:posix-standard/posix] A compatibility layer for running Linux binary executables natively on Windows 10 and 11 using a Linux image such as Ubuntu, Debian, or OpenSUSE among others, acting as an upgrade and replacement for Windows Services for UNIX.
[src:posix-standard/posix] The first distribution available was Ubuntu.
[src:posix-standard/posix] From AT&T Research implements a POSIX layer on top of the Win32 APIs.
[src:posix-standard/posix] although the support remains largely incomplete and not fully interoperable with POSIX-compliant implementations.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] The **Single UNIX Specification** (**SUS**) is a standard for computer operating systems, compliance with which is required to qualify for using the "UNIX" trademark.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] The standard specifies programming interfaces for the C language, a command-line shell, and user commands.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] The core specifications of the SUS known as *Base Specifications* are developed and maintained by the Austin Group, which is a joint working group of IEEE, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22/WG 15 and The Open Group.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] If an operating system is submitted to The Open Group for certification and passes conformance tests, then it is deemed to be compliant with a UNIX standard such as UNIX 98 or UNIX 03.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Very few BSD and Linux-based operating systems are submitted for compliance with the Single UNIX Specification, although system developers generally aim for compliance with POSIX standards, which form the core of the Single UNIX Specification.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] The latest SUS consists of two parts: the *base specifications* technically identical to POSIX, and the X/Open Curses specification.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] The SUS emerged from multiple 1980s efforts to standardize operating system interfaces for software designed for variants of the Unix operating system.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] The need for standardization arose because enterprises using computers wanted to be able to develop programs that could be used on the computer systems of different manufacturers without reimplementing the programs.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Unix was selected as the basis for a standard system interface partly because it was manufacturer-neutral.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] In 1984, the UNIX user group called /usr/group published the results of their standardization effort for programming interfaces in their 1984 /usr/group standard, which became basis for what would become the POSIX.1-1988 standard.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] In 1985, AT&T published System V Interface Definition (SVID), a specification of UNIX System V programming interfaces.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] In 1988, standardization efforts resulted in **IEEE 1003** (also registered as **ISO/IEC 9945**), or **POSIX.1-1988**, which loosely stands for **Portable Operating System Interface**.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] The X/Open Portability Guide (XPG) was a precursor to the SUS, published by the X/Open Company, a consortium of companies established in 1984.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] The guides were published in the following years.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] In the early 1990s, a separate effort known as the Common API Specification or Spec 1170 was initiated by several major vendors, who formed the COSE alliance in the wake of the Unix wars.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] In 1993, Spec 1170 was assigned by COSE to X/Open for fasttrack.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] In October 1993, a planned transfer of UNIX trademark from Novell to X/Open was announced; it was finalized in 2nd quarter of 1994.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Spec 1170 would eventually become the Single Unix Specification.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] In 1994, the X/Open Company released the **Single UNIX Specification**.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] This was a repackaging of the X/Open Portability Guide (XPG), Issue 4, Version 2.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Sources differ on whether X/Open Curses, Issue 4, Version 2 was part of this SUS; its copyright date is given as 1996.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] X/Open Curses, Issue 4 was published in 1995.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] In October 1994, X/Open indicated they were going to refer to Spec 1170 as '"Single-Unix" specification'.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] The SUS was at the core of the UNIX 95 brand.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] This version had 1168 programming interfaces.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] In 1996, X/Open merged with Open Software Foundation (OSF) to form The Open Group.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] In 1997, the Open Group released the **Single UNIX Specification, Version 2**.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] and was at the core of the UNIX 98 brand.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] This version had 1434 programming interfaces.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Beginning in 1998, a joint working group of IEEE, ISO JTC 1 SC22 and The Open Group known as the Austin Group began to develop the combined standard that would be known as the core of **Single UNIX Specification, Version 3** and as POSIX.1-2001.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] and is at the core of the UNIX 03 brand.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] The Base Specifications are technically identical to **POSIX.1-2001**, which is IEEE Std 1003.1-2001.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] This version had 1742 programming interfaces.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] An authorized guide is available for the version.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] In 2004, a new edition of the POSIX.1-2001 standard was released, incorporating two technical corrigenda.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] It is called IEEE Std 1003.1, 2004 Edition.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Some informally call it POSIX.1-2004, but this is not an official identification.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] In December 2008, the Austin Group published a new major revision of SUS and POSIX.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] This is the Single UNIX Specification, Version 4 (SUSv4).
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] The Base Specifications are technically identical to **POSIX.1-2008**, which is IEEE Std 1003.1-2008.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] This version had 1833 interfaces, of which 1191 were in the System Interfaces section.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Technical Corrigendum 1 mostly targeted internationalization, and also introduced a role-based access model.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] A trademark *UNIX V7* (not to be confused with V7 UNIX, the version of Research Unix from 1979) was created to mark compliance with SUS Version 4.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Technical Corrigendum 2 was published in September 2016, leading into *IEEE Std 1003.1-2008, 2016 Edition* and *Single UNIX Specification, Version 4, 2016 Edition*.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] In January 2018, an "administrative rollup" edition was released.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] It incorporates Single UNIX Specification version 4 TC1 and TC2, and is technically identical to the 2016 edition.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] The Base Specifications are technically identical to **POSIX.1-2017**, which is IEEE Std 1003.1-2017.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] The standard user command line and scripting interface is the POSIX shell, an extension of the Bourne Shell based on an early version of the Korn Shell.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Other user-level programs, services and utilities include awk, echo, ed, vi, and hundreds of others.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Required program-level services include basic I/O (file, terminal, and network) services.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] It is called **PCTS** or the **POSIX Certification Test Suite**.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Additionally, SUS includes CURSES (XCURSES) specification, which specifies 372 functions and 3 header files.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] All in all, SUSv3 specifies 1742 interfaces.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Note that a system need not include source code derived in any way from AT&T Unix to meet the specification.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] For instance, IBM OS/390, now z/OS, qualifies as UNIX despite having no code in common.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Only AIX and macOS have UNIX 03 or later certifications. z/OS is mainly a non-UNIX OS, still current, but on old UNIX certification.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Other products are discontinued, on pre-UNIX 03 certifications, or have let their certifications lapse.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] AIX version 7, at either 7.1 TL5 (or later) or 7.2 TL2 (or later) are registered as UNIX 03 compliant.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] AIX version 7, at 7.2 TL5 (or later) are registered as UNIX V7 compliant.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Older versions were previously certified to the UNIX 95 and UNIX 98 marks.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] HP-UX 11i V3 Release B.11.31 remains registered as UNIX 03 compliant on HPE Integrity Servers despite the end of support for HP-UX by HPE.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Previous releases were registered as UNIX 95.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Apple macOS (formerly known as Mac OS X and OS X) is registered as UNIX 03 compliant.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] The first version registered was Mac OS X 10.5 Leopard, certified on October 26, 2007 (on x86 systems).
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] All versions of macOS from Mac OS X Leopard to macOS 10.15 Catalina, except for OS X Lion, have been registered on Intel-based systems, and all versions from macOS 11 Big Sur, the successor to macOS Catalina, up to macOS 26 Tahoe have been registered on both x86-64 and ARM64 systems.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] UnixWare 7.1.3 and later is registered as UNIX 95 compliant.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] OpenServer 5 and 6 are registered as UNIX 93 compliant.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] IBM z/OS 1.2 and higher is registered as UNIX 95 compliant. z/OS 1.9, released on September 28, 2007, and subsequent releases "better align" with UNIX 03.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] EulerOS 2.0 for the x86-64 architecture was registered as UNIX 03 compliant.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] The UNIX 03 conformance statement shows that the standard C compiler is from the GNU Compiler Collection (gcc), and that the system is a Linux distribution of the Red Hat Enterprise Linux family.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] The UNIX 03 certification expired in September 2022 and has not been renewed.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Stratus Technologies DNCP Series servers running FTX Release 3 were registered as UNIX 93 compliant.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Inspur K-UX 2.0 and 3.0 for the x86-64 architecture were certified as UNIX 03 compliant.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] The UNIX 03 conformance statement for Inspur K-UX 2.0 and 3.0 shows that the standard C compiler is from the GNU Compiler Collection (gcc), and that the system is a Linux distribution of the Red Hat family.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] SGI IRIX 6.5 was registered as UNIX 95 compliant.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] IBM OS/390 was registered as UNIX 95 compliant beginning with the V2R4 release.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] The last Reliant UNIX versions were registered as UNIX 95 compliant (XPG4 hard branding).
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Solaris 11.4 was previously registered as UNIX v7 compliant in 2018.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Solaris 11 and Solaris 10 were registered as UNIX 03 compliant on 32-bit and 64-bit x86 (X86-64) and SPARC systems.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Solaris 8 and 9 were registered as UNIX 98 compliant on 32-bit x86 and SPARC systems; 64-bit x86 systems were not supported.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Solaris 2.4 and 2.6, on both x86 and SPARC, were certified to the UNIX 93 and UNIX 95 marks respectively.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Solaris 2.5.1 was also registered as UNIX 95 compliant on the PReP PowerPC platform in 1996, but the product was withdrawn before more than a few dozen copies had been sold.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Tru64 UNIX V5.1A and later were registered as UNIX 98 compliant.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Developers and vendors of Unix-like operating systems such as Linux, FreeBSD, and MINIX typically do not certify their distributions and do not install full POSIX utilities by default.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] For Linux, the pax command is usually not installed; furthermore, the pax command packages available for Linux often lack the pax file format support required by POSIX.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Sometimes, SUS compliance can be improved by installing additional packages, but very few Linux systems can be configured to be completely conformant.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] The Linux Standard Base was formed in 2001 as an attempt to standardize the internal structures of Linux-based systems for increased compatibility.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] It is based on the POSIX specifications, the Single UNIX Specification, and other open standards, and also extends them in several areas; but there are some conflicts between the LSB and the POSIX standards.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Few Linux distributions actually go through certification as LSB compliant.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Darwin, the open source subset of macOS, has behavior that can be set to comply with UNIX 03.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] Darwin uses a 4.4BSD-derived pax command, which lacks multibyte support for filenames.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] FreeBSD previously had a "C99 and POSIX Conformance Project" which aimed for compliance with a subset of the Single UNIX Specification, and documentation where there were differences.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] FreeBSD man pages sometimes indicate deviations from POSIX and thus SUS in their STANDARDS sections.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] OpenBSD man pages sometimes indicate deviations from POSIX and thus SUS in their STANDARDS sections.
[src:posix-standard/single-unix-specification] MINIX pax command does not support the pax file format and thereby fails POSIX.1-2001.
